[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.  

When you have a weak, distributional hand with 5 of partner's suit an immediate jump to game is usually the best approach. If he has a good hand you will probably make the contract. If he is minimum then you might get a preemptive effect and stop your LHO from entering the bidding.

This is a good example. Partner may be lucky and make 4\H. But if they had had an opportunity to compete the opponents might well be able to make 4\S.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - Major Suit Openings"]
[Board "14"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "W:JT65.T96.T5.AK84 3.AKJ873.AQJ3.73 Q84.42.K986.QJ92 AK972.Q5.742.T65"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "N"]
1H pass 1S pass 3H pass 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[Category "Basic Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "basic_bidding/major_suit_openings"]
[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.  

You can't support partner's \Hs with only 2 of them so you bid your nice \S suit. Partner then jumps to 3\H. Now  

Here's where a lot of players go wrong. Since they only promised 4 \Ss with their first response they think they should now rebid them to show partner they had 5. And this <b>MIGHT</b> work if it turns out partner has 3 \Ss. Not only is this a risky bid, it is unnecessary. When partner jump rebid \Hs he showed 16-18 points and 6 \Hs. So you know of an 8-card fit and you know you should be in game. Bid 4\H.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - Major Suit Openings"]
[Board "15"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "W:84.KJ43.T86.9732 AQT93.A92.KQJ3.4 65.QT76.A95.JT86 KJ72.85.742.AKQ5"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "6S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "N"]
1S pass 2C pass 2D pass 4S pass 4NT pass 5D pass 6S all pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[Category "Basic Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "basic_bidding/major_suit_openings"]
[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.  

As soon as partner opens 1\S you know you will settle for nothing less than the \S game. The problem with bidding 4\S right now is that partner will take you for the "weak-distributional-with-five-trumps" hand. So you temporize by first bidding 2\C. Partner rebids 2\D.  

You now jump to 4\S, completing the picture of an opening hand with good \S support. Partner bids 4NT. What say you? 

This is Blackwood so you answer 5\D for one Ace. Partner says 6\S.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - Major Suit Openings"]
[Board "16"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "W:J432.QJ.A42.7652 75.AKT764.KJ.QJT Q96.2.8753.AK943 AKT8.9853.QT96.8"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "N"]
1H pass 3H pass 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[Category "Basic Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "basic_bidding/major_suit_openings"]
[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.  

You could bid 1\S. Many would do so, thinking "I have to show partner my \S suit."

In fact, you don't have to show partner your \S suit. You already know of a partnership 9-card fit in \Hs, so there is no reason to search for a possible 8-card fit in \Ss.

With 11 points and 4 trumps you bid 3\H, a limit raise. Partner raises to game.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - Major Suit Openings"]
[Board "17"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "W:54.T532.A874.J82 A962.AKJ74.T5.73 J73.98.K32.KQT54 KQT8.Q6.QJ96.A96"]
[Declarer "S"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "N"]
1H pass 1S pass 2S pass 4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[Category "Basic Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "basic_bidding/major_suit_openings"]
[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.  

You <b>MIGHT</b> jump to 2NT to "show your points". However, a notrump bid now would deny a 4-card \S suit. Instead, your priority is to show that Major, so you respond 1\S. Partner bids 2\S. What do you say next? 

Partner would not support a response which might be 4 cards unless he had 4 himself. Knowing that you have two opening hands facing each other, each containing 4 \Ss, you bid the \S game.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - Major Suit Openings"]
[Board "18"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "W:2.42.A9432.Q8543 AT975.KQ.KT5.AJ7 J43.AT9853.8.KT2 KQ86.J76.QJ76.96"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "4S"]
